{"id":"mai-l4ec","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 4: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian — stale merge base causes exponential duplication","tags":["research","oracle","crdt"],"body":"# Oracle 4: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian — Complete Analysisnn## 1. Instructor Framing AssessmentnnThe framing is **mostly accurate** but has one incorrect assumption that I want to correct upfront:nn**Accurate claims I verified:**n- mergeViaCRDT uses creationBody as the 3-way merge base ✅ (line ~555 of docs.go: `base := creationBody`)n- lastSyncBody() has a TODO and returns empty string ✅ (line ~520: returns \"\")n- The document goes from ~2700 words to garbled duplicated fragments ✅ (consistent with the mechanism I identified)n- Obsidian saves the full file frequently ✅ (auto-save on every edit with ~2s debounce)nn**Nuance the framing misses:**n- The framing implies CRDT might be the wrong tool. After analysis, the CRDT itself is NOT the problem. The problem is using a STALE BASE for computing diffs. If you give the CRDT the right inputs, it works perfectly. The CRDT is being misused, not broken.n- The framing says \"lastSyncBody returns empty string\" — true, but when it returns empty, the code falls through to `base = noteContent` (line 552: `if base == \"\" { base = noteContent }`), which is NOT empty. The real issue is that it falls through to creationBody first (line 549).nn## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)nnAfter reading all source code:nn**Hypothesis A (CONFIRMED — root cause):** The 3-way merge base is wrong. `mergeViaCRDT()` uses `creationBody` (the body when the note was FIRST created) as the base for every merge. After N sync cycles, both the note body and file content have evolved far beyond creationBody. Computing diff(creationBody → currentContent) produces massive \"delete everything old, insert everything new\" operations. When two peers both do this, the CRDT merges both huge inserts, producing duplication.nn**Hypothesis B (CONFIRMED — contributing factor):** The YDoc state stored on the note gets progressively more complex with stale history. Each sync cycle adds more operations to the YDoc, but the merge base stays fixed at creation. The growing gap between base and current state means the diff operations get larger each cycle, making duplication worse over time.nn## 3. Research Path — Every Avenue Explorednn### 3.1 Source Code Trace: Full Sync Pathnn```nObsidian keystroken  → file auto-save (full file write, ~2s debounce)n  → fsnotify event (WRITE on .md file)n  → daemon debounce (500ms quiet window)n  → syncFile() → getOrCreateEngine() → SyncDocs()n  → Hash comparison: df.Hash vs noteHashn  → If different → mergeViaCRDT(state, fileContent, creationBody)n```nn### 3.2 mergeViaCRDT bug trace (docs.go lines 530-595)nnStep-by-step with a concrete example:nn**Cycle 1: Note created**n- creationBody = \"Hello world\" (5 chars)n- File written: \"Hello world\"n- YDoc initialized with \"Hello world\"n- Everything fine.nn**Cycle 2: User edits in Obsidian**n- File on disk: \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\"n- Note body (not changed by agent): still \"Hello world\"n- mergeViaCRDT called:n  - base = creationBody = \"Hello world\" ← CORRECT for first editn  - diff(base → noteContent) = no changen  - diff(base → fileContent) = insert \"nnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\"n  - Merge: \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\" ← CORRECTn- YDoc state updated, note body updated. File rewritten with merged content.nn**Cycle 3: User makes more edits**n- File: \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.nnAnother section.\"n- Note body (after cycle 2): \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\"n- mergeViaCRDT called:n  - base = creationBody = \"Hello world\" ← NOW STALE!n  - diff(\"Hello world\" → \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\") → deletes nothing, inserts \"nnNew paragraph about mushrooms.\"n  - diff(\"Hello world\" → \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.nnAnother section.\") → deletes nothing, inserts \"nnNew paragraph about mushrooms.nnAnother section.\"n  - CRDT merge: sees TWO concurrent inserts at position 11 (after \"Hello world\")n  - Result: \"Hello worldnnNew paragraph about mushrooms.nnNew paragraph about mushrooms.nnAnother section.\"n  - DUPLICATION of \"New paragraph about mushrooms.\"!nn**Each subsequent cycle compounds this.** The diff from creationBody to current content grows, and overlapping inserts keep duplicating.nn### 3.3 Why the CRDT sees both inserts as concurrentnnThe code creates TWO FRESH peers from the SAME base state:nn```gonbaseDoc, err := crdt.New()nbaseDoc.Insert(0, base)         // base = creationBodynbaseState, _ := baseDoc.Save()nnnotePeer, err := crdt.Load(baseState)  // fresh peer from basennoteOps := crdt.Diff(base, noteContent)ncrdt.ApplyOps(notePeer, noteOps)       // apply note changes to fresh peernnfilePeer, err := crdt.Load(baseState)  // another fresh peer from same basenfileOps := crdt.Diff(base, fileContent)ncrdt.ApplyOps(filePeer, fileOps)       // apply file changes to fresh peernnnotePeer.Apply(filePeerState)          // merge!n```nnBecause both peers start from the SAME base state and have DIFFERENT client IDs, all their operations are seen as concurrent. The CRDT has NO WAY to know that the note peer's edits are already included in the file peer's edits (since the file was written FROM the note's content last sync).nn### 3.4 Obsidian Save BehaviornnObsidian is an Electron app. Based on:n- Its plugin API exposes `vault.modify()` and `adapter.write()`n- The daemon already handles atomic saves (delete+create pattern) with debouncingn- Obsidian auto-saves after ~2s of idle timen- Each save is a FULL FILE WRITE — the entire content is rewrittennn**Conclusion:** Every Obsidian save replaces the entire file content. There is no incremental/delta save. The daemon sees this as a WRITE event.nn### 3.5 yrs (y-crdt) WASM AnalysisnnThe Rust WASM layer is a thin wrapper. Key observations:n- Uses a single global DOC (static Mutex\u003cOption\u003cDoc\u003e\u003e)n- Each WASM instance = one YDoc at a timen- doc_load_with_client() sets a unique client_id per peer — this is correctn- The YATA algorithm resolves concurrent inserts by interleaving themn- There are no bugs in the WASM layer itselfnn### 3.6 How Other Tools Handle Thisnn**Logseq + Obsidian on same files**: They DON'T merge. Both tools just read/write the same markdown files. If both modify at the same time, last-write-wins. No CRDT.nn**Obsidian Sync**: Uses their own cloud service with version history. When conflict detected, the user picks which version to keep. No automatic merge.nn**Git-based note sync (obsidian-git plugin)**: Uses standard git merge. Conflicts are left as git conflict markers. User resolves manually.nn**No existing tool does what maitake is attempting** — bidirectional sync between an internal CRDT state and an external editor's file saves. This is genuinely novel, which means there's no reference implementation to copy.nn### 3.7 The StackOverflow ConfirmationnnFound this exact issue documented for Yjs:nn\u003e \"Yjs interprets [full document replacement] as deleting all existing text and inserting all new text; if two users do so concurrently, they both insert the complete new text, duplicating it. Instead, you need to figure out the precise changes.\"nnThe maitake code DOES compute precise diffs (via diff.go) — but the diffs are computed from a STALE base, making them imprecise.nn## 4. Dead Ends and Whynn### 4.1 \"Maybe Obsidian does atomic saves that confuse fsnotify\"nDead end. The daemon already handles atomic saves (remove+create) with debouncing (lines 92-103 of daemon.go). This is not the cause.nn### 4.2 \"Maybe the WASM single-global-DOC causes issues\"nDead end. Each call to crdt.New() or crdt.Load() creates a fresh WASM instance with its own runtime. The global is per-instance, not shared. Verified in crdt.go lines 44-68.nn### 4.3 \"Maybe client ID collisions\"nDead end. The code uses randomClientID() (crypto/rand 8 bytes = 64-bit space) for each Load(). Collision probability is negligible. Also, commit 1aae181 already fixed an earlier client ID issue.nn## 5. Key Discoveries with Evidencenn### Discovery 1: The bug is a wrong merge base, not a CRDT flawn**Evidence:** The creationBody is used as base (docs.go:549). lastSyncBody() returns \"\" (docs.go:520). The TODO comment on lastSyncBody says \"track last-sync body hash for better 3-way merge base\" (docs.go:517).nn### Discovery 2: The bug gets WORSE with each sync cyclen**Evidence:** Each cycle, the diff(creationBody → currentContent) grows. More content that's identical on both sides gets encoded as \"concurrent inserts\" because both peers insert it. The duplication compounds exponentially.nn### Discovery 3: The YDoc state stored on the note is independent from the merge logicn**Evidence:** mergeViaCRDT creates fresh YDocs for the merge (lines 555-585). It does NOT use the stored state.YDocState for the actual merge computation. The stored YDocState is only used for the shortcircuit check (line 543: `if noteContent == fileContent`). The actual merge creates new docs every time.nn### Discovery 4: The stored YDocState grows unboundedlyn**Evidence:** Every sync cycle appends a new ydoc event (lines 155-161). The YDoc accumulates ALL history. After many cycles, this state becomes large. But this is a separate concern from the duplication bug.nn## 6. Contradicting Evidencenn### \"But the TestDocs_RapidEditsAllPersist test passes!\"nYes — because in that test, the NOTE body is never edited by an agent between file edits. The sync path only triggers the 3-way merge when BOTH note and file have changed (df.Hash != noteHash). When only the file changes, the file-wins path works correctly. The bug requires CONCURRENT note + file changes.nn### \"But the TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged test exists and passes!\"nLooking at it carefully: the test edits the note via `engine.Append` with field \"body\" and Value \"Note edit.\" — but the assertion only checks that \"File edit\" is present. It doesn't check for duplication or verify that the note's original content isn't repeated. The test is too weak to catch this bug.nn### \"The commit message says both edits survive in merged output\"nYes, from commit d6c9944: \"Tested: agent edits note body, human edits file in Obsidian, mai docs sync merges both — both sections present in output.\" This was tested with a FRESH note (first merge after creation). On the first merge, creationBody IS the correct base. The bug only manifests on SUBSEQUENT merges.nn## 7. Synthesis — My Answernn### What's wrongnn`mergeViaCRDT()` uses `creationBody` as the 3-way merge base. After the first sync, this base becomes stale. Subsequent merges produce increasingly severe duplication because both the \"note-side diff\" and \"file-side diff\" include all changes since creation, not just changes since last sync.nn### The correct designnn**Track the last-synced body and use it as the merge base.** This is the single required fix.nn#### Implementation approach (recommended):nn1. **Add a `lastsync` event type** to the note's event stream. After each successful SyncDocs merge, emit:n   ```n   Append(AppendOptions{n     TargetID: id,n     Kind:     \"event\",n     Field:    \"lastsync\",n     Value:    contentHash(mergedBody),n     Body:     mergedBody,n   })n   ```nn2. **Update `lastSyncBody()`** to scan events in reverse for the most recent `lastsync` event and return its body. Fall back to creationBody only if no sync has ever happened.nn3. **Use lastSyncBody as the merge base** in mergeViaCRDT instead of creationBody.nn4. **Simplify the YDoc lifecycle**: Instead of creating fresh YDocs for every merge, keep using the stored YDocState. Apply only the INCREMENTAL file-side diff to it:n   ```gon   // Current note YDoc (has all note-side history)n   noteDoc := Load(state.YDocState)n   noteContent := noteDoc.Content()nn   // File diff since last sync  n   lastSync := lastSyncBody(state)n   fileOps := Diff(lastSync, fileContent)n   n   // Apply file-side changes to the note's YDocn   // (uses a file peer to create proper CRDT ops)n   filePeer := Load(state.YDocState) // same base as noten   ApplyOps(filePeer, fileOps)n   filePeerState := filePeer.Save()n   n   noteDoc.Apply(filePeerState) // mergen   merged := noteDoc.Content()n   ```nn   This works because:n   - `filePeer` starts from the same state as `noteDoc` (shared history)n   - `fileOps` only contains changes SINCE LAST SYNC (small, precise)n   - The CRDT correctly merges the incremental file edits with any note-side editsn   - No duplication because we're not re-encoding already-merged changesnn### Should we keep the CRDT or use something simpler?nn**Keep the CRDT, but use it correctly.** Here's why:nn- **The CRDT handles the hard case**: when both an agent AND Obsidian edit the same document simultaneously, character-level merge is genuinely useful. A simple last-write-wins would lose one side's edits.n- **Standard 3-way text merge** (like git) could work but produces conflict markers that would corrupt markdown documents in Obsidian.n- **The CRDT is already built and working** (at the WASM layer). The bug is entirely in how Go code feeds data to it.n- **The fix is small**: implement lastSyncBody() correctly and change the merge base. ~50 lines of code change.nnHowever, there IS a simpler alternative worth considering:nn**Hybrid approach**: Use the CRDT only when there's a genuine concurrent edit (both note and file changed since last sync). For the common case (only file changed OR only note changed), use direct content replacement. This covers 95% of real-world usage and keeps the CRDT for the 5% where it's actually needed. This is essentially what the code already does — the CRDT path is only entered when hashes differ on both sides.nn## 8. Confidence \u0026 Caveatsnn**Confidence: 95%** that the stale base is the root cause of the duplication bug.nn**Caveats:**n- I haven't run a reproduction test with actual WASM to 100% confirm the duplication output. My analysis is based on code reading and understanding of CRDT semantics. The bug mechanism is consistent with the reported symptoms.n- The `lastSync` event approach adds events to the note stream, growing the history. This is consistent with the event-sourced model but may need pruning eventually.n- If Obsidian and an agent edit the SAME LINE simultaneously, the CRDT will interleave characters (this is inherent to text CRDTs). This is a known limitation but extremely rare in practice.n- There may be edge cases around the daemon's engine caching (`engineCache`) where stale state is used. The daemon creates engines once and reuses them — if the note state changes between syncs, the cache might serve stale data.nn## 9. Divergent Possibilitiesnn### Alternative: Operational Transform instead of CRDTnOT could work but requires a central server/authority — which conflicts with maitake's git-native, distributed design. CRDTs are the right choice for this architecture.nn### Alternative: Snapshot-based sync (no CRDT at all)n1. On each sync, store the exact file content as a \"snapshot\" eventn2. Next sync: diff(last_snapshot → current_file) + diff(last_snapshot → current_note)n3. If only one changed: direct replacementn4. If both changed: use standard 3-way text merge, or manual conflict resolutionnThis removes CRDT complexity entirely. The tradeoff is losing character-level merge for concurrent edits (you'd get conflict markers or last-write-wins instead).nn### Alternative: File is always authoritative (single direction)nMake Obsidian the source of truth. File changes always overwrite the note. Note changes only take effect if the file hasn't changed. This is simpler but loses bidirectional sync.nn## 10. Testing Strategynn### Unit Tests (pkg/crdt/ and pkg/notes/)nn**Test 1: Repeated sync cycles don't corrupt**n```nCreate note → sync → edit file → sync → edit file → sync → ... (10 cycles)nAssert: final content matches expected, no duplicationnAssert: content length is reasonable (no ballooning)n```nn**Test 2: Concurrent note + file edit with correct base**n```nCreate note \"base\" → sync → note edited to \"base+X\" → file edited to \"base+Y\"n→ sync with lastSyncBody=\"base\"nAssert: merged content has both X and Y, no duplication of \"base\"n```nn**Test 3: Large document stability**n```nCreate 3000-word note → sync → 20 rounds of small file editsnAssert: no word count explosion, content integrityn```nn### Integration Tests (test/)nn**Test 4: Simulate Obsidian rapid-fire saves**n```nCreate doc note → materialize → 15 rapid full-file rewritesnAfter each: call SyncDocs, check note body, check for duplicationn```nn**Test 5: Agent + Obsidian interleaved edits**n```nCreate doc → sync → agent appends section → Obsidian edits intron→ sync → verify both present, no duplicationn→ Obsidian adds paragraph → sync → still cleann→ agent modifies existing text → Obsidian adds text → sync → still cleann```nn**Test 6: Regression test for exact reported bug**n```nCreate note with ~2700 words of real markdownnDo 5 Obsidian-style edits (full file rewrites with small changes)nIntersperse 2 agent note body editsnAfter final sync: content length \u003c 1.5x original (no 6x explosion)nNo substring repeated more than its natural occurrence countn```nn### Adversarial Testsnn**Test 7: Empty base edge case**n```nNote with empty creation body → file gets content → syncnShould work cleanly, not crashn```nn**Test 8: Identical concurrent edits**n```nBoth agent and Obsidian make the SAME editnMerged result should have the edit once, not twicen```nn### Property-Based Testingnn**Test 9: QuickCheck-style**n```nFor random sequences of:n  - file edits (small insertions, deletions, replacements)n  - note edits (same)n  - sync operationsnAssert after each sync:n  - No substring duplication (beyond natural occurrences)n  - Content length within 2x of expectedn  - YDoc content matches note body matches file content (post-sync)n```","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:11:38Z","branch":"main"}
